Using Linear Regression to Explain Deputies Votes

Jose Manoel Ferreira

1 de outubro de 2018

  # campos:
  # "sequencial_candidato" :(character) id do candidato
  # "nome": (character)
  # "uf": (character)
  # "partido": (character)
  # "quantidade_doacoes": (integer)
  # "quantidade_doadores": (integer) nmero de doadores diferentes
  # "total_receita": (double) soma em R$ das doaes
  # "media_receita": (double) mdia das doaes
  # "recursos_de_outros_candidatos/comites": (double) quantia em R$ das doaes provenientes de outros candidatos ou comite partidrio
  # "recursos_de_pessoas_fisicas": (double) quantia em R$ das doaes provenientes de outros CPFs
  # "recursos_de_pessoas_juridicas": (double) quantia em R$ das doaes provenientes de outros CNPJ
  # "recursos_proprios": (double) quantia em R$ das doaes provenientes do prprio candidato
  # "recursos_de_partido_politico": (double) quantia em R$ das doaes provenientes do partido poltico do candidato
  # "votos": (integer) varivel alvo. Se refere ao nmero de votos na campanha de 2006 e 2010
  # "quantidade_despesas": (integer)
  # "quantidade_fornecedores": (integer) nmero de fornecedores/despesas diferentes
  # "total_despesa": (double) soma em R$ das despesas de campanha
  # "media_despesa": (double) mdia das despesas de campanha
  # "cargo": (character)
  # "Sexo":  (character)
  # "grau": (character) grau de instruo do candidato
  # "estado_civil": (character)
  # "ocupacao": (character) ocupao do candidato

Building our dataframes

data2006 <- read.csv(("data/eleicoes_2006.csv"))
data2010 <- read.csv(("data/eleicoes_2010.csv"))
data2006_2010 <-read.csv(("data/eleicoes_2006_e_2010.csv"))

Removing the NA

data2006 <- na.omit(data2006)
data2010 <- na.omit(data2010)
data2006_2010 <- na.omit(data2006_2010)

Its important to see the correlation between the variables, it will show to us the dependence between variables

2006

data2006.correlation1 <- data2006 %>% select(-c(sequencial_candidato, nome, estado_civil, ano, cargo))

data2006.correlation <- data2006.correlation1  %>%
  mutate(uf = as.numeric(uf)) %>%
  mutate(partido = as.numeric(partido)) %>%
  mutate(sexo = as.numeric(sexo)) %>%
  mutate(grau = as.numeric(grau)) %>%
  mutate(ocupacao = as.numeric(ocupacao))
  

ggpairs(data2006.correlation, axisLabels = "none")

Seeing the correlation betweend the variables we can say that the variable whit the best correlation whit votos is total_despesa 0.658 flollowed by total_receita 0.635 whitch makes totally sense, because the total_receita is the values used to pay the expense and its represented by total_despesas. > * Greater correation is whit: > total_despesas corr: 0.658 > total_receita corr: 0.635 > * Smaller correlation is whit: > uf corr: - 0.0318 > partido: - 0.048

2010

votos is our target variable, so lets take a look and the correlation between votos and other variables. > * Greater correation is whit: > total_despesas corr: 0.637 > total_receita corr: 0.626 > * Smaller correlation is whit: > media_despesas corr: 0.0715 > uf corr: - 0.0425

2006 and 2010

As we can see weve got a very similar result in both years, total_receita and total_despesa as the greater correlation and uf was the smalest.

data2010.correlation1 <- data2010 %>% select(-c(sequencial_candidato, nome, estado_civil, ano, cargo))

data2010.correlation <- data2010.correlation1  %>%
  mutate(uf = as.numeric(uf)) %>%
  mutate(partido = as.numeric(partido)) %>%
  mutate(sexo = as.numeric(sexo)) %>%
  mutate(grau = as.numeric(grau)) %>%
  mutate(ocupacao = as.numeric(ocupacao))
  

ggpairs(data2010.correlation, axisLabels = "none")

Multiple Regression Linear Model Whit all numeric variables

1. A multiple regresson model whit all variables is able to explain the y variation (total of votos) in 2006 and 2010?

2006

As we can see weve got a \(R_a^2\) and \(R^2\) whit 0.5779 and 0.5488 respectively. As close to 1 is better to explain the model, but it seems not enough and even adjusting the R-squared we got a minimum increasing. So the model whit all variables does not weel explains the total of votos. Also there is too many categoric variables making an extense model being difficult to visualise.

data2006.lm = lm(data2006$votos ~ data2006$uf + data2006$partido  + data2006$quantidade_doacoes + data2006$quantidade_doadores + data2006$total_receita + data2006$media_receita + data2006$recursos_de_outros_candidatos.comites + data2006$recursos_de_pessoas_fisicas + data2006$recursos_de_pessoas_juridicas + data2006$recursos_proprios + data2006$recursos_de_partido_politico + data2006$quantidade_despesas + data2006$quantidade_fornecedores + data2006$total_despesa + data2006$media_despesa + data2006$sexo + data2006$grau + data2006$estado_civil + data2006$ocupacao)

2. Compere the regressiond made to 2006 and 2010. Which are the difference/similarities noticed:

Looking to the residual charts we can notice that the greater amount is close to zero, it is good because there is not big difference between the new model results copared whit the original one. But the scale to residual chart of 2010 is greter then 2006 it means that had some errors whit a considerable value. The variables has almost the same correlation value, it looks so same to both years.

2010

### 3. Are all variables useful to the regression model? is there any redundant varialbe? Alaysis to 2006 and 2010 separately.

No, not all variable are usefull to the model, for example cargo, there is only one cargo and year which is DEPUTADO FEDERAL and 2006 respectively. Also there is redudant variables, media_receita which is the mediam of all receita so it have a strong correlation whit total_receita, so it not necessary to have both variables in the model. Also weve some variables whit a strong correlation as quantidade_doacoes and quantidade_doadores whit 0.997 in both years; total_receita and total_despesas whit 0.99; total_receita and total_despesas whit 0.988, those variable together are not good to explain the model, so should chouse one of each variable strong correlated.

4. If there is redudant variables or not explained, make a new model excluding those variables and compare the new model with the one that has all variables (e.g.should explain using R2 and RSE)

In order to reach a better model weve choose a few variables, numeric ones whit a good significance value, but the R-squared and adjusted got was smaller then the one whit all varialbes, also not a good regression model, not 2006 nor 2010. * 2006: R-squared: 0.4896, Adjusted R-squared: 0.4887 * 2010: R-squared: 0.4232, Adjusted R-squared: 0.4224

5. Make a regression including both years 2006 and 1010 together. Which differencies/similitaries are notices coparing whit the models whit individual year?

Putting all year together and we notice that correlation does not change too much, and the year in all variables show a small correlation factor. Almost same residual chart, but more close to 2010. R-squared: 0.5082, Adjusted R-squared: 0.4909 Was a few better then other year Even reproducing the model whit fewer variables, removing the redundant ones whe still getting a R2 and RSE between 0.4 and 0.5

data2006_2010.correlation1 <- data2006_2010 %>% select(-c(sequencial_candidato, nome, estado_civil, cargo))

data2006_2010.correlation <- data2006_2010.correlation1  %>%
  mutate(uf = as.numeric(uf)) %>%
  mutate(partido = as.numeric(partido)) %>%
  mutate(sexo = as.numeric(sexo)) %>%
  mutate(grau = as.numeric(grau)) %>%
  mutate(ocupacao = as.numeric(ocupacao))
  

ggpairs(data2006_2010.correlation, axisLabels = "none")

data2006_2010.lm = lm(data2006_2010$votos ~ data2006_2010$uf + data2006_2010$partido  + data2006_2010$quantidade_doacoes + data2006_2010$quantidade_doadores + data2006_2010$total_receita + data2006_2010$media_receita + data2006_2010$recursos_de_outros_candidatos.comites + data2006_2010$recursos_de_pessoas_fisicas + data2006_2010$recursos_de_pessoas_juridicas + data2006_2010$recursos_proprios + data2006_2010$recursos_de_partido_politico + data2006_2010$quantidade_despesas + data2006_2010$quantidade_fornecedores + data2006_2010$total_despesa + data2006_2010$media_despesa + data2006_2010$sexo + data2006_2010$grau + data2006_2010$estado_civil + data2006_2010$ocupacao + data2006_2010$ano)
